  "signature": "(-,+,+,+)",
  "convention": "The coordinate $r$ is the areal radius, $r \\in [0, R]$, where $R$ is the stellar radius. The parameter $r_s = 2GM/c^2$ is the Schwarzschild radius of the star. The solution assumes a uniform (incompressible) perfect fluid and matches the exterior Schwarzschild metric at $r = R$. Units with $c = 1$ are used throughout.",
  "history": "Karl Schwarzschild derived two exact solutions to the Einstein field equations in 1916. The first, now called the exterior Schwarzschild solution, describes the vacuum spacetime outside a spherical mass. The second, derived shortly afterward in the same year, describes the interior of a static, spherically symmetric star composed of an incompressible perfect fluid of uniform density. This interior solution was among the first exact solutions to the field equations with a matter source.¶The solution reveals a fundamental limit on the compactness of a star: the central pressure diverges when $r_s/R = 8/9$, which means no static configuration can have $r_s > 8R/9$ regardless of the equation of state. This Buchdahl limit (later generalized by Hans Buchdahl in 1959) is more restrictive than the Schwarzschild radius condition and represents a physical bound on stellar compactness in general relativity.¶Despite its idealized assumption of uniform density — which is acausal, as incompressible fluids transmit disturbances instantaneously — the interior Schwarzschild metric remains a standard and pedagogically important exact solution, commonly used to illustrate gravitational redshift, hydrostatic equilibrium in GR, and the junction conditions connecting interior and exterior spacetimes.",
  "references": [
    "schwarzschild1916b",
    "misner1973"
  ],
